S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The part of a building on land that is extending above navigable water. Depending on the vertical clearance vessels can pass under the building above navigable water.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Special Purpose Mark
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of an aid to navigation which signifies some special purpose.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A mark may be a beacon, a buoy, a signpost or may take another form.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Firing Danger Area Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate a firing danger area, usually at sea.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Target Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any object toward which something is directed. The distinctive marking or instrumentation of a ground point to aid its identification on a photograph.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Marker Ship Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark marking the position of a ship which is used as a target during some military exercise.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Degaussing Range Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate a degaussing range.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Barge Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark of relevance to barges.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cable Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the position of submarine cables or the point at which they run on to the land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Spoil Ground Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the limit of a spoil ground.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Outfall Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the position of an outfall or the point at which it leaves the land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: ODAS
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Ocean Data Acquisition System.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Recording Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to record data for scientific purposes.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Seaplane Anchorage Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate a seaplane anchorage.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Recreation Zone Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate a recreation zone.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Private Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A privately maintained mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mooring Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a mooring or moorings.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: LANBY
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A large buoy designed to take the place of a lightship where construction of an offshore light station is not feasible.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Leading Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Aids to navigation or other indicators so located as to indicate the path to be followed. Leading marks identify a leading line when they are in transit.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Measured Distance Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark forming part of a transit indicating one end of a measured distance.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Notice Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A notice board or sign indicating information to the mariner.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: TSS Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a Traffic Separation Scheme.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Anchoring Prohibited Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating an anchoring prohibited area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Berthing Prohibited Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that berthing is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Overtaking Prohibited Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that overtaking is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Two-Way Traffic Prohibited Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a one-way route.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Reduced Wake Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that vessels must not generate excessive wake.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Speed Limit Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that a speed limit applies.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Stop Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the place where the bow of a ship must stop when traffic lights show red.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: General Warning Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that special caution must be exercised in the vicinity of the mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sound Ship's Siren Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that a ship should sound its siren or horn.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Restricted Vertical Clearance Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the minimum vertical space available for passage.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Maximum Vessel's Draught Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the maximum draught of vessel permitted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Restricted Horizontal Clearance Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the minimum horizontal space available for passage.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Strong Current Warning Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark warning of strong currents.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Berthing Permitted Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that berthing is allowed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Overhead Power Cable Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating an overhead power cable.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Channel Edge Gradient Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the gradient of the slope of a dredge channel edge.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Telephone Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the presence of a telephone.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ferry Crossing Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that a ferry route crosses the ship route; often used with a 'sound ship's siren' mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Pipeline Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the position of submarine pipelines or the point at which they run on to the land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Anchorage Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating an anchorage area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Clearing Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate a clearing line.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Control Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the location at which a restriction or requirement exists.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Diving Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that diving may take place in the vicinity.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Refuge Beacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark providing or indicating a place of safety.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Foul Ground Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a foul ground.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Yachting Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark installed for use by yachtsmen.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Heliport Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating an area where helicopters may land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: GNSS Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a location at which a GNSS position has been accurately determined.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Seaplane Landing Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating an area where seaplanes land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Entry Prohibited Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that entry is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Work in Progress Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating that work (generally construction) is in progress.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mark With Unknown Purpose
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark whose detailed characteristics are unknown.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Wellhead Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a borehole that produces or is capable of producing oil or natural gas.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Channel Separation Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the point at which a channel divides separately into two channels.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Marine Farm Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the existence of a fish, mussel, oyster or pearl farm/culture.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Artificial Reef Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating the existence or the extent of an artificial reef.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ice Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark, used year round, that may be submerged when ice passes through the area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Nature Reserve Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to define the boundary of a nature reserve.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fish Aggregating Device
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A fish aggregating (or aggregation) device (FAD) is a man-made object used to attract ocean going pelagic fish such as marlin, tuna and mahi-mahi (dolphin fish). They usually consist of buoys or floats tethered to the ocean floor with concrete blocks or adrift.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Wreck Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the existence of a wreck.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Customs Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the existence of a customs checkpoint.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Causeway Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark used to indicate the existence of a causeway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Wave Recorder
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A surface following buoy used to measure wave activity.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Jetski Prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A mark indicating a jetski prohibited area.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Topmark/Daymark Shape
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The shape a topmark or daymark exhibits.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cone (Point Up)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Is where the vertex points up.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cone (Point Down)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Is where the vertex points down.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sphere
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A curved surface all points of which are equidistant from a fixed point within, called the centre.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 Spheres
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Two spheres, one above the other. Two black spheres are commonly used as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark (isolated danger).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cylinder
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of point a closed curve, especially a circle (in which case the figure is circular cylinder, its ends being parallel circles).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Board
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Usually of rectangular shape, made from timber or metal and used to provide a contrast with the natural background of a daymark. The actual daymark is often painted on to this board.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: X-Shaped
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Having a shape or a cross-section like the capital letter X.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Upright Cross
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A cross with one vertical member and one horizontal member; that is, similar in shape to the character '+'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cube (Point Up)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A cube standing on one of its vertexes. A cube is a solid contained by six equal squares, a regular hexahedron.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 Cones (Point to Point)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices together in the centre.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 Cones (Base to Base)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their bases together in the centre and their vertices pointing up and down.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rhombus
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A plane figure having four equal sides and equal opposite angles (two acute and two obtuse); an oblique equilateral parallelogram.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 Cones (Points Upward)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices pointing up.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 Cones (Points Downward)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices pointing down.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Besom (Point Up)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A bundle of rods or twigs. A besom, point up is where the thicker (untied) end of the besom is at the bottom.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Besom (Point Down)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A bundle of rods or twigs. A besom, point down is where the thinner (tied) end of the besom is at the bottom.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Flag
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A flag mounted on a short pole.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sphere Over a Rhombus
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A sphere located above a rhombus.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Square
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A plane figure with four right angles and four equal straight sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rectangle (Horizontal)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A horizontal rectangle is where the two longer opposite sides are standing horizontally.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rectangle (Vertical)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A rectangle is a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length. A vertical rectangle is where the two longer opposite sides are standing vertically.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Trapezium (Up)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel, and which stands on its longer parallel side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Trapezium (Down)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel, and which stands on its shorter parallel side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Triangle (Point Up)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A figure having three angles and three sides, and which has a vertex at the top.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Triangle (Point Down)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A figure having three angles and three sides, and which has a side at the top.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A perfectly round plane figure whose circumference is everywhere equidistant from its centre.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Two Upright Crosses (One Over the Other)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Two upright crosses, generally vertically disposed one above the other.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: T-Shape
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Having a shape like the capital letter T.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Triangle Pointing Up Over a Circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A triangle, vertex uppermost, located above a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Upright Cross Over a Circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An upright cross located above a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rhombus Over a Circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A rhombus located above a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Circle Over a Triangle Pointing Up
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A circle located over a triangle, vertex uppermost.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Other Shape (See Shape Information)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An uncommon and/or non-standardized shape as textually described using an associated attribute.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Tubular
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Having the form of or consisting of a tube.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Fog Signal
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of the various means of generating the fog signal.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The classification 'horn' is the generic term for fog signals 'nautophone', 'reed' and 'tyfon'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Explosive
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A signal produced by the firing of explosive charges.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Diaphone
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A diaphone uses compressed air and generally emits a powerful low-pitched sound, which often concludes with a brief sound of suddenly lowered pitch, termed the 'grunt'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Siren
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A type of fog signal apparatus which produces sound by virtue of the passage of air through slots or holes in a revolving disk.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Nautophone
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A horn having a diaphragm oscillated by electricity.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Reed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: [1] A reed uses compressed air and emits a weak, high pitched sound. [2] Any of various water or marsh plants with a firm stem. (Concise Oxford English Dictionary)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Tyfon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A diaphragm horn which operates under the influence of compressed air or steam.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bell
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A ringing sound with a short range.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Whistle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A distinctive sound made by a jet of air passing through an orifice. The apparatus may be operated automatically, by hand or by air being forced up a tube by waves acting on a buoy.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Gong
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A sound produced by vibration of a disc when struck.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Horn
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A horn uses compressed air or electricity to vibrate a diaphragm and exists in a variety of types which differ greatly in their sound and power.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Radar Transponder Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of radar transponder beacon based on functionality.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ramark, Radar Beacon Transmitting Continuously
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radar marker beacon which continuously transmits a signal appearing as a radial line on a radar screen, the line indicating the direction of the beacon. Ramarks are intended primarily for marine use. The name 'ramark' is derived from the words radar marker.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Racon, Radar Transponder Beacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radar beacon which returns a coded signal which provides identification of the beacon, as well as range and bearing. The range and bearing are indicated by the location of the first character received on the radar screen. The name 'racon' is derived from the words radar beacon.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Leading Racon/Radar Transponder Beacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radar beacon that may be used (in conjunction with at least one other radar beacon) to indicate a leading line.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal Group
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The number of signals, the combination of signals or the morse character(s) within one period of full sequence.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal Period
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The time occupied by an entire cycle of intervals of light and eclipse.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of Nominal Range
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The luminous range of a light in a homogenous atmosphere in which the meteorological visibility is 10 sea miles.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Radio Station
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of radio services offered by a radio station.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A radiobeacon is a radio transmitter which emits a distinctive or characteristic signal on which a bearing may be taken.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Circular (Non-Directional) Marine or Aero-Marine Radiobeacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radio station which need not necessarily be manned, the emissions of which, radiated around the horizon, enable its bearing to be determined by means of the radio direction finder of a ship.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Directional Radiobeacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A special type of radiobeacon station the emissions of which are intended to provide a definite track for guidance.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rotating Pattern Radiobeacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A special type of radiobeacon station emitting a beam of waves to which a uniform turning movement is given, the bearing of the station being determined by means of an ordinary listening receiver and a stop watch. Also referred to as a rotating loop radiobeacon.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Consol Beacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A type of long range position fixing beacon.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Radio Direction-Finding Station
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radio station intended to determine only the direction of other stations by means of transmission from the latter.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Coast Radio Station Providing QTG Service
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radio station which is prepared to provide QTG service; that is to say, to transmit upon request from a ship a radio signal, the bearing of which can be taken by that ship.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Aeronautical Radiobeacon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A radio beacon designed for aeronautical use.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Decca
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The Decca Navigator System is a high accuracy, short to medium range radio navigational aid intended for coastal and landfall navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Loran C
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A low frequency electronic position fixing system using pulsed transmissions at 100 Khz.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Differential GNSS
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Differential GNSS is implemented by placing a GNSS monitor receiver at a precisely known location. Instead of computing a navigation fix, the monitor determines the range error to every GNSS satellite it can track. These ranging errors are then transmitted to local users where they are applied as corrections before computing the navigation result.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Toran
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An electronic position fixing system used mainly by aircraft.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Omega
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A long-range radio navigational aid which operates within the VLF frequency band. The system comprises eight land based stations.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Syledis
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A ranging position fixing system operating at 420-450 MHz over a range of up to 400 Km.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Chaika
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A low frequency electronic position fixing system using pulsed transmissions at 100 Khz.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Radio Telephone Station
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The equipment needed at one station to carry on two way voice communication by radio waves only.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: AIS Base Station
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An AIS shore station for use by competent authorities to provide AIS service, manage the data link and enable effective ship to shore / shore to ship transmission of information.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Effective Intensity
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The luminous intensity of a fictitious juxtaposed steady-burning point light source that would appear to exhibit a luminosity equal to that of the rhythmic point light source it describes. The apparent reduction in intensity of the rhythmic light is subjective and is due to the nature of the response of the eye of the observer.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Estimated Range of Transmission
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The estimated range of a non-optical electromagnetic transmission.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The estimated range (distance) assumes 'in vacuo' transmission and a standard antenna height of 5 metres. Thus it gives a hint to the mariner whether they are likely to receive transmission at a certain distance from an object.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Light Visibility
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The specific visibility of a light, with respect to the light's intensity and ease of recognition.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: High Intensity
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Non-marine lights with a higher power than marine lights and visible from well off shore (often 'Aero' lights).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Low Intensity
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Non-marine lights with lower power than marine lights.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Faint
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A decrease in the apparent intensity of a light which may occur in the case of partial obstructions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Intensified
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light in a sector is intensified (that is, has longer range than other sectors).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Unintensified
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light in a sector is unintensified (that is, has shorter range than other sectors).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Visibility Deliberately Restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light sector is deliberately reduced in intensity, for example to reduce its effect on a built-up area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Obscured
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Said of the arc of a light sector designated by its limiting bearings in which the light is not visible from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Partially Obscured
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: This value specifies that parts of the sector are obscured.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Visible in Line of Range
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Lights that must be in line to be visible.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Exhibition Condition of Light
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The outward display of the light.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Light Shown Without Change of Character
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light shown throughout the 24 hours without change of character.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Daytime Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light which is only exhibited by day.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fog Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light which is exhibited in fog or conditions of reduced visibility.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Night Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light which is only exhibited at night.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Flare Bearing
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The bearing about which the light flare symbol is rotated to be displayed in ECDIS.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The initial flare bearing is calculated by ENC production software systems. The attribute flare bearing may also be populated manually to cartographically align the light flare along, for example, a transit or leading line (noting that the in such cases the bearing to be encoded will be the reciprocal (+/- 180 degrees) of the bearing encoded for the navigational line).

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal Generation
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The mechanism used to generate a fog or light signal.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Automatically
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Signal generation is initiated by a self regulating mechanism such as a timer or light sensor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: By Wave Action
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The signal is generated by the motion of the sea surface such as a bell in a buoy.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: By Hand
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The signal is generated by a manually operated mechanism such as a hand cranked siren.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: By Wind
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The signal is generated by the motion of air such as a wind driven whistle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Radio Activated
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Activated by radio signal.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Call Activated
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Activated by making a call to a manned station.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Major Light
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: A statement expressing if a light is considered to be a major light in terms of ECDIS display in a particular area.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Major light is only intended to provide an indication to the ECDIS that the light is considered to be an important light in terms of its display. As such this is a cartographic attribute to aid the compiler in determining the most appropriate display for a light; it is not intended to be used as a formal classification method for lights.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Light
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of different light types.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: All lights are considered to be marine lights unless the category of light indicates otherwise.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Directional Function
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light illuminating a sector of very narrow angle and intended to mark a direction to follow.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Leading Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light associated with other lights so as to form a leading line to be followed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Aero Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An aero light is established for aeronautical navigation and may be of higher power than marine lights and visible from well offshore.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Air Obstruction Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light marking an obstacle which constitutes a danger to air navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Flood Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A broad beam light used to illuminate a structure or area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Strip Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light whose source has a linear form generally horizontal, which can reach a length of several metres.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Subsidiary Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light placed on or near the support of a main light and having a special use in navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Spotlight
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A powerful light focused so as to illuminate a small area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Front
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rear
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Lower
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Upper
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Term used with leading lights to describe the position of the light on the lead as viewed from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Emergency
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light available as a backup to a main light which will be illuminated should the main light fail.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bearing Light
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light which enables its approximate bearing to be obtained without the use of a compass.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Horizontally Disposed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A group of lights of identical character and almost identical position, that are disposed horizontally.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Vertically Disposed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A group of lights of identical character and almost identical position, that are disposed vertically.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Offshore Platform
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of an offshore raised structure.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Oil Rig
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A temporary mobile structure, either fixed or floating, used in the exploration stages of oil and gas fields.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Production Platform
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A term used to indicate a permanent offshore structure equipped to control the flow of oil or gas. It does not include entirely submarine structures.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Observation/Research Platform
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A platform from which one's surroundings or events can be observed, noted or recorded such as for scientific study.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Articulated Loading Platform
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A metal lattice tower, buoyant at one end and attached at the other by a universal joint to a concrete filled base on the seabed. The platform may be fitted with a helicopter platform, emergency accommodation and hawser/hose retrieval.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Single Anchor Leg Mooring
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A rigid frame or tube with a buoyancy device at its upper end, secured at its lower end to a universal joint on a large steel or concrete base resting on the seabed, and at its upper end to a mooring buoy by a chain or wire.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mooring Tower
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A platform secured to the seabed and surmounted by a turntable to which ships moor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Artificial Island
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A man-made structure usually built for the exploration or exploitation of marine resources, marine scientific research, tidal observations, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Floating Production, Storage and Off-Loading Vessel
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An offshore facility consisting of a moored tanker/barge by which the product is extracted, stored and exported.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Accommodation Platform
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A platform used primarily for eating, sleeping and recreation purposes.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Navigation, Communication and Control Buoy
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A floating structure with control room, power and storage facilities, attached to the seabed by a flexible pipeline and cables.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Floating Oil Tank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A floating structure, anchored to the seabed, for storing oil.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Condition
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The various conditions of buildings and other constructions.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The default 'condition' should be considered to be completed, undamaged and working normally.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Under Construction
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Being built but not yet capable of function.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ruined
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A structure in a decayed or deteriorated condition resulting from neglect or disuse, or a damaged structure in need of repair.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Under Reclamation
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An area of the sea, a lake or the navigable part of a river that is being reclaimed as land, usually by the dumping of earth and other material.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Wingless
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A windmill or wind turbine from which the vanes or turbine blades are missing.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Planned Construction
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Detailed planning has been completed but construction has not been initiated.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Pile
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of pile, driven into the earth as a foundation or support for a structure.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Stake
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elongated wood or metal pole embedded in the seabed to serve as a marker or support.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Post
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A vertical piece of timber, metal or concrete forced into the earth or seabed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Tripodal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A single structure comprising 3 or more piles held together (sections of heavy timber, steel or concrete), and forced into the earth or seabed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Piling
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A number of piles, usually in a straight line, and usually connected or bolted together.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Area of Piles
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A number of piles, usually in a straight line, but not connected by structural members.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Pipe
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A vertical hollow cylinder of metal, wood, or other material forced into the earth or seabed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mooring Post
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A post where to which something (such as a craft) can be moored.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Building Shape
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The specific shape of the building.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: High-Rise Building
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A building having many storeys.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Pyramid
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A polyhedron of which one face is a polygon of any number of sides, and the other faces are triangles with a common vertex.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cylindrical
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Shaped like a cylinder, which is a solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of its points a closed curve, especially a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Spherical
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Shaped like a sphere, which is a body the surface of which is at all points equidistant from the centre.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cubic
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A shape the sides of which are six equal squares; a regular hexahedron.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Silo/Tank
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification based on the product for which a silo or tank is used.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Silo in General
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A large storage structure used for storing loose materials.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Tank in General
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A fixed structure for storing liquids.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Grain Elevator
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A storage building for grain. Usually a tall frame, metal or concrete structure with an especially compartmented interior.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Water Tower
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A tower supporting an elevated storage tank of water.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Lateral Mark
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of lateral marks in the IALA Buoyage System.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: There are two international buoyage regions, A and B, between which lateral marks differ. When top-marks, retro reflectors and/or lights are fitted to these marks, they are encoded as separate features.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Port-Hand Lateral Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the port boundary of a navigational channel or suggested route when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage".

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Starboard-Hand Lateral Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the starboard boundary of a navigational channel or suggested route when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage".

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Preferred Channel to Starboard Lateral Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: At a point where a channel divides, when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage", the preferred channel (or primary route) is indicated by a modified port-hand lateral mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Preferred Channel to Port Lateral Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: At a point where a channel divides, when proceeding in the "conventional direction of buoyage", the preferred channel (or primary route) is indicated by a modified starboard-hand lateral mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Right-Hand Side of the Waterway
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the right-hand side of the inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Left-Hand Side of the Waterway
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the left-hand side of the inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Right-Hand Side of the Channel
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the right-hand side of a channel of an inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Left-Hand Side of the Channel
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the left-hand side of a channel of an inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bifurcation of the Waterway
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a bifurcation of the inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bifurcation of the Channel
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a bifurcation of a channel of an inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Channel Near the Right Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates that the channel is near the right bank.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Channel Near the Left Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates that the channel is near the left bank.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Channel Cross-Over to the Right Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates that the channel crosses from the left to the right bank.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Channel Cross-Over to the Left Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates that the channel crosses from the right to the left bank.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Danger Point or Obstacles at the Right-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a danger point or obstacles at the right-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Danger Point or Obstacles at the Left-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a danger point or obstacles at the left-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Turn Off at the Right-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a turn off at the right-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Turn Off at the Left-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a turn off at the left-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Junction at the Right-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a junction at the right-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Junction at the Left-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a junction at the left-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Harbour Entry at the Right-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a harbour entry at the right-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Harbour Entry at the Left-Hand Side
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a harbour entry at the left-hand side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bridge Pier Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates a bridge pier in an inland waterway.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Entry From a Lake to a Narrower Waterway, Right Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the right bank of the entry from a lake or a lake-like expansion to a section of the waterway which is narrower.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Entry From a Lake to a Narrower Waterway, Left Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indicates the left bank of the entry from a lake or a lake-like expansion to a section of the waterway which is narrower.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Change Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Change bank.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Continue Along Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Continue along bank.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Cardinal Mark
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The four quadrants (north, east, south and west) are bounded by the true bearings NW-NE, NE-SE, SE-SW and SW-NW taken from the point of interest. A cardinal mark is named after the quadrant in which it is placed. The name of the cardinal mark indicates that it should be passed to the named side of the mark.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Cardinal marks are used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where a mariner will find safe navigable water.Cardinal marks do not have a distinctive shape but are normally pillar or spar. They are always painted in yellow and black horizontal bands and their distinctive double cone top-marks are always black. (Note that such top-marks are encoded as separate TOPMAR objects). Cardinal marks may also have a special system of flashing white lights and if such lights are fitted they are encoded as separate LIGHTS objects.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: North Cardinal Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing NW-NE taken from the point of interest; it should be passed to the north side of the mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: East Cardinal Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing NE-SE taken from the point of interest. It should be passed to the east side of the mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: South Cardinal Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing SE-SW taken from the point of interest; it should be passed to the south side of the mark.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: West Cardinal Mark
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Quadrant bounded by the true bearing SW-NW taken from the point of interest; it should be passed to the west side of the mark.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Elevation
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The altitude of the ground level of a feature, measured from a specified vertical datum.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Maximum Display Scale
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The value considered by the Data Producer to be the maximum (largest) scale at which the data is to be displayed before it can be considered to be grossly overscaled.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Minimum Display Scale
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The smallest intended viewing scale for the data.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Temporal Variation
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: An assessment of the likelihood of change over time.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Extreme Event
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Indication of the possible impact of a significant event (for example hurricane, earthquake, volcanic eruption, landslide, etc), which is considered likely to have changed the seafloor or landscape significantly.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Likely to Change and Significant Shoaling Expected
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Continuous or frequent change (for example river siltation, sand waves, seasonal storms, icebergs, etc) that is likely to result in new significant shoaling.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Likely to Change But Significant Shoaling Not Expected
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Continuous or frequent change (for example sand wave shift, seasonal storms, icebergs, etc) that is not likely to result in new significant shoaling.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Likely to Change
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Continuous or frequent change to non-bathymetric features (for example river siltation, glacier creep/recession, sand dunes, buoys, marine farms, etc).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Unlikely to Change
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Significant change to the seafloor is not expected.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Unassessed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Not having been assessed.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Orientation Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of a bearing.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Distance Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the horizontal accuracy of horizontal clearances and distances.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The error is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character must not be encoded.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Change Types
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Different categories or kinds of modifications that can be made to data, positions, or objects. For example, changes may involve updates to position, orientation, or attributes of an object.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Change Details
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Specific information or description regarding modifications or updates made to an object, system, or dataset. This term typically includes the nature, scope, and reason for the change, as well as any impact it may have on operations or functionality.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Obscured Sector
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A portion or sector of a navigational aid, such as a light or beacon, that is blocked or obscured from view due to obstacles (e.g., landforms, buildings, or other structures). In marine or aviation navigation, it usually refers to an area where the light signal or visibility is intentionally or unintentionally reduced or not visible to vessels or aircraft.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Contact Address
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Direction or superscription of a letter, package, etc., specifying the name of the place to which it is directed, and optionally a contact person or organisation who should receive it.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Feature Name
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Provides the name of an entity, defines the national language of the name, and provides the option to display the name at various system display settings.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Fixed Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: An active period of a single fixed event or occurrence, as the date range between discrete start and end dates.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Dates must be encoded in the format YYYYMMDD; using 4 digits for the calendar year (YYYY) and, optionally, 2 digits for the month (MM) (for example April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, the values are replaced with dashes (-). The date range of a recurring event or occurrence must be encoded using periodicDateRange.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Position Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of a position.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The expected input is the maximum of the two-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Textual information about the feature. The information may be provided as a string of text or as a file name of a single external text file that contains the text.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: At least one of the sub-attributes file reference or text must be populated.The sub-attribute file reference is generally used for long text strings or those that require formatting, however, there is no restriction on the type of text (except for lexical level) that can be held in files referenced by sub-attribute file reference.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Multiplicity of Features
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The number of features of identical character that exist as a co-located group.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Light Sector
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Directional Character
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A directional light is a light illuminating a sector of very narrow angle and intended to mark a direction to follow.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Orientation
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: (1) The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the feature. (2) In ECDIS, the mode in which information on the ECDIS is being presented. Typical modes include: north-up - as shown on a nautical chart, north is at the top of the display; Ships head-up - based on the actual heading of the ship, (e.g. Ships gyrocompass); course-up display - based on the course or route being taken.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Periodic Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The active period of a recurring event or occurrence.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Radar Wave Length
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The distance between two successive peaks (or other points of identical phase) on an electromagnetic wave in the radar band of the electromagnetic spectrum.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Describes the characteristics of a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Additional textual information about a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. The sector limit specifies the limits of the sector In a clockwise direction around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit One
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector limit one specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit Two
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector limit two specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal Sequence
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light/sound and eclipse/silence for all light characteristics or sound signals.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Spatial Accuracy
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Provides an indication of the vertical and horizontal positional uncertainty of bathymetric data, optionally within a specified date range.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Textual Description
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Encodes the file name of a single external text file that contains the text in a defined language, which provides additional textual information that cannot be provided using other allowable attributes for the feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the vertical accuracy of depths, heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Encodes the vertical uncertainty associated with any vertical measurement.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Navigable Track
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: The role given to the navigable part of the navigation line.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Spatial Quality
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: The indication of the quality of the locational information for features in a dataset.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Aton Status Information
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: This refers to the current operational status or condition of an Aid to Navigation (AtoN). It provides details about whether the navigational aid (such as a buoy, light, or beacon) is functioning properly, temporarily out of service, under maintenance, or has any other status that affects its operation or visibility to mariners.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Aids to Navigation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A visual, acoustical, or radio device, external to a ship, designed to assist in determining a safe course or a vessel's position, or to warn of dangers and/or obstructions. Aids to navigation usually include buoys, beacons, fog signals, lights, radio beacons, leading marks, radio position fixing systems and GNSS which are chart-related and assist safe navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigation Line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A straight line extending towards an area of navigational interest and generally generated by two navigational aids or one navigational aid and a bearing.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The extent of the navigation line depends on the visibility of the navigational aid(s). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Recommended Track
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A route which has been specially examined to ensure so far as possible that it is free of dangers and along which ships are advised to navigate.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Recommended tracks include all channels recommended for hydrographic reasons to lead safely between shoal depths. The use of such tracks is generally left to the discretion of the mariner and will depend on the vessel's draught, the state of the tide, adequacy of navigational aids and so on (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation. In the case of a two-way recommended track only one value of orientation is encoded; the other value can be deduced (that is, the value encoded + 180 degrees).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Equipment
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The implements used in an operation or activity.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Structure Object
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Something (such as a house, tower, bridge, etc.) that is built by putting parts together and that usually stands on its own.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Generic Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A floating object moored to the bottom in a particular (charted) place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Navigational buoys may be classified according to: (a) their shape, appearance, or construction, such as barrel, can, cask, conical, cylindrical, dan, keg, nun, pillar, spar, spherical,or topmark buoy; (b) their colour, such as black, chequered, green, red buoy; (c) their location, such as bifurcation, fairway, junction, mid-channel, middle-ground, or turning buoy; (d) the various kinds of hazards or dangers to navigation which they mark, such as bar, isolated danger, fish trap, obstruction, spoil ground, telegraph or wreck buoy; (e) their particular purpose or use, such as anchor, anchorage, compass adjustment, dredging, farewell (or landfall), marker, quarantine, station (or watch), or warping buoy.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Generic Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fixed artificial navigation mark that can be recognized by its shape, colour, pattern, topmark or light character, or a combination of these. It may carry various additional aids to navigation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This term is not commonly used when the navigation mark can be classified as a lighthouse.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Landmark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Any prominent object at a fixed location on land which can be used in determining a location or a direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Daymark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: (1) The identifying characteristics of an aid to navigation which serve to facilitate its recognition against a daylight viewing background. On those structures that do not by themselves present an adequate viewing area to be seen at the required distance, the aid is made more visible by affixing a daymark to the structure. A daymark so affixed has a distinctive colour and shape depending on the purpose of the aid. (2) An unlighted navigational mark.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fog Signal
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A warning signal transmitted by a vessel, or aid to navigation, during periods of low visibility. Also, the device producing such a signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar Reflector
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A device capable of, or intended for, reflecting radar signals.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A radar reflector is usually a tetrahedron or pentagonal corner reflector to facilitate reflection towards the sender (International Maritime Dictionary, 2nd Ed.).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar Transponder Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A transponder beacon transmitting a coded signal on radar frequency, permitting an interrogating craft to determine the bearing and range of the transponder.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The feature 'radar transponder beacon' is only used to encode the technical equipment independent of the structure on which it is located (for example a beacon, light-vessel or tower).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radio Station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A place equipped to transmit radio waves. Such a station may be either stationary or mobile, and may also be provided with a radio receiver.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The transmission of a radio station may serve to provide mariners with a line of position (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The feature 'radio station' is used to encode the point of transmission of the signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Retroreflector
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A means of distinguishing unlighted marks at night. Retroreflective material is secured to the mark in a particular pattern to reflect back light.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The body carrying the retro-reflector is a separate feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Air Obstruction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An air obstruction light is a light marking an obstacle which constitutes a danger to air navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light All Around
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An all around light is a light that is visible over the whole horizon of interest to marine navigation and having no change in the characteristics of the light.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Fog Detector
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fog detector light is a light used to automatically determine conditions of visibility which warrant the turning on or off of a sound signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Sectored
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A light presenting different appearances (in particular, different colours) over various parts of the horizon of interest to maritime navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Float
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A boat-like structure used instead of a light buoy in waters where strong streams or currents are experienced, or when a greater elevation than that of a light buoy is necessary.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The light of a light float is a separate feature, handled as with buoys, beacons, etc.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Vessel
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A distinctively marked vessel anchored or moored at a charted point, to serve as an aid to navigation. By night, it displays a characteristic light(s) and is usually equipped with other devices, such as fog signal, submarine sound signal, and radio-beacon, to assist navigation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The light(s), fog signal etc. of a light vessel are separate features, handled as with buoys, beacons, etc.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Offshore Platform
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A permanent offshore structure, either fixed or floating.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pile
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A long heavy timber or section of steel, wood, concrete, etc., forced into the earth or seafloor to serve as a support, as for a pier, or to resist lateral pressure; or as a free standing pole within a marine environment.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Silo/Tank
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A large storage structure used for storing loose materials, liquids and/or gases.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cardinal Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A cardinal buoy is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary S-32 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Emergency Wreck Marking Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An emergency wreck marking buoy is a buoy moored on or above a new wreck, designed to provide a prominent (both visual and radio) and easily identifiable temporary first response.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Installation Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An installation buoy is a buoy used for loading tankers with gas or oil.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Isolated Danger Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An isolated danger buoy is a buoy moored on or above an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lateral Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lateral buoy is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well-defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Mooring Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A buoy secured to the bottom by permanent moorings with means for mooring a vessel by use of its anchor chain or mooring lines.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Safe Water Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A safe water buoy is used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Special Purpose/General Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A special purpose buoy is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cardinal Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A cardinal beacon is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Isolated Danger Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An isolated danger beacon is a beacon erected on an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Safe Water Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A safe water beacon is used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Special Purpose/General Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A special purpose beacon is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lateral Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lateral beacon is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Wind Turbine
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A tower and associated equipment that generates electrical power from wind. They can be sited offshore and may be either fixed or floating.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Vertical Datum of Data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Any level surface (for example Mean Sea Level) taken as a surface of reference to which the elevations within a data set are reduced. Also called datum level, reference level, reference plane, levelling datum, datum for heights.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Data Coverage
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographical area that describes the coverage and extent of spatial objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Local Direction of Buoyage
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which the navigational system of marks has been established in relation to a specific direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigational System of Marks
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which the navigational system of marks has been established in relation to a specific direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sounding Datum
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The horizontal plane or tidal datum to which soundings have been reduced. Also called datum for sounding reduction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Quality of Bathymetric Data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the quality of the bathymetric data exists.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Generic Light
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A source of light, usually artificial, that serves as an aid to navigation, providing visibility and guidance, especially in low-light conditions. It could be mounted on various structures like buoys, beacons, or lighthouses to indicate a specific location or navigational point.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dangerous Feature
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A characteristic or element in the environment that poses a potential risk to navigation or safety. This could include hazards such as rocks, submerged objects, shallow waters, or man-made structures that could endanger vessels or other forms of transportation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Synthetic AIS Aid To Navigation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A virtual or synthetic Aid to Navigation (AtoN) transmitted via the Automatic Identification System (AIS). Unlike a physical AtoN, which exists in the real world (like buoys or lighthouses), a synthetic AIS AtoN is created in the AIS network to provide navigational information to mariners about a point of interest or hazard, even if no physical object is present at that location. It helps in improving situational awareness.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Physical AIS Aid to Navigation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) message 21 transmitted from a physical Aid to Navigation, or transmitted from an AIS station for an Aid to Navigation which physically exists.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Virtual AIS Aid to Navigation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) message 21 transmitted from an AIS station to simulate on navigation systems an Aid to Navigation which does not physically exist.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Aton Aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Used to identify an aggregation of two or more objects. This aggregation may be named content of categoryOfAggregation should be put in information attribute when converting to S-57.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Aton Association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Used to identify an association between two or more objects. The association may be named content of categoryOfAssociation should be put in information attribute when converting to S-57
